Configuring transactional Kafka producers in a Spring application ensures that messages are sent atomically and reliably. This is particularly important for maintaining data integrity when integrating with systems like Apache Flink, which rely on exactly-once semantics. Here’s how you can set up transactional producers in a Spring Boot application:

### Step-by-Step Configuration

#### 1. Add Dependencies
Ensure your project includes the necessary dependencies for Kafka and Spring Kafka.

```xml
<!-- Maven Example -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.kafka</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-kafka</artifactId>
</dependency>

<!-- Avro serialization dependency -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.confluent</groupId>
    <artifactId>kafka-avro-serializer</artifactId>
    <version>7.0.1</version> <!-- Use the latest version available -->
</dependency>
```

#### 2. Configure Kafka Producer
Configure your Kafka producer to use transactional settings and Avro serialization.

```yaml
spring:
  kafka:
    bootstrap-servers: localhost:9092
    producer:
      key-serializer: org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer
      value-serializer: io.confluent.kafka.serializers.KafkaAvroSerializer # Use Avro serializer
      transaction-id-prefix: my-producer-
      schema.registry.url: http://localhost:8081
```

#### 3. Create a Transactional Kafka Template Bean

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerConfig;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.kafka.core.DefaultKafkaProducerFactory;
import org.springframework.kafka.core.KafkaTemplate;

@Configuration
public class KafkaProducerConfig {

    @Bean
    public KafkaTemplate<String, OrderCreatedEvent> kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate() {
        return new KafkaTemplate<>(producerFactory("order-created"));
    }

    private ProducerFactory<String, OrderCreatedEvent> producerFactory(String topic) {
        Map<String, Object> props = new HashMap<>();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        props.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, KafkaAvroSerializer.class); // Use Avro serializer
        props.put("schema.registry.url", "http://localhost:8081");
        props.put("transaction.id.prefix", "my-producer-"); // Transactional producer ID prefix

        return new DefaultKafkaProducerFactory<>(props);
    }
}
```

#### 4. Implement Transaction Management in Service Layer
Ensure that your service layer manages transactions properly.

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.kafka.core.KafkaTemplate;
import org.springframework.kafka.support.SendResult;
import org.springframework.util.concurrent.ListenableFutureCallback;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
public class OrderServiceImpl implements OrderService {

    private final KafkaTemplate<String, OrderCreatedEvent> kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate;

    @Autowired
    public OrderServiceImpl(KafkaTemplate<String, OrderCreatedEvent> kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate) {
        this.kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate = kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate;
    }

    @Override
    public void createOrder(Order order) {
        // Business logic to validate and process the order

        OrderCreatedEvent event = new OrderCreatedEvent();
        event.setEventType("ORDER_CREATED");
        event.setTimestamp(System.currentTimeMillis());
        event.setOrderId(order.getId());
        event.setCustomerId(order.getCustomer().getId());
        event.setItems(order.getItems());
        event.setTotalAmount(order.getTotalAmount());

        // Start a transaction
        kafkaOrderCreatedTemplate.executeInTransaction((txKafkaTemplate) -> {
            txKafkaTemplate.send("order-created", event);
        });

        // Commit the transaction (automatically handled by KafkaTemplate)
    }
}
```

