@Service
public class InventoryManagementSystem {

    public void reserveStock(String orderId, List<OrderItem> items) {
        // Logic to reserve stock
        System.out.println("Reserving stock for order " + orderId);
    }

    public void releaseStock(String orderId) {
        // Ensure idempotent release of reserved stock
        if (!isStockReserved(orderId)) {
            return;
        }

        // Logic to release reserved stock
        System.out.println("Releasing stock for order " + orderId);
    }

    private boolean isStockReserved(String orderId) {
        // Check if the stock has already been reserved
        // This could be a database query or another check mechanism
        return true;  // Placeholder logic, replace with actual implementation
    }
}
```

### 2. Use Distributed Locks

Use distributed locks to ensure that compensating actions are executed only once even in the presence of retries.

#### Example: Using Redis for Distributed Locks

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.StringRedisTemplate;

@Service
public class InventoryManagementSystem {

    @Autowired
    private StringRedisTemplate redisTemplate;

    public void releaseStock(String orderId) {
        // Acquire a distributed lock to ensure idempotency
        if (!acquireLock(orderId)) {
            return;
        }

        try {
            // Logic to release reserved stock
            System.out.println("Releasing stock for order " + orderId);
        } finally {
            // Release the lock
            releaseLock(orderId);
        }
    }

    private boolean acquireLock(String orderId) {
        String key = "stock-release-lock:" + orderId;
        return redisTemplate.opsForValue().setIfAbsent(key, "locked", 60, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
    }

    private void releaseLock(String orderId) {
        String key = "stock-release-lock:" + orderId;
        redisTemplate.delete(key);
    }
}
```

### 3. Use Transactional Idempotency

Ensure that compensating actions are transactionally idempotent by using database transactions to track the state of operations.

#### Example: Using Database Transactions for Idempotency

